result.execSummary:
The defendant Kaysi Marie Guffy was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Subject to good time and work release.

miscConds.notes: $265.60 fine/costs to be paid to the Clerk of Court Office. Bond to be applied and remainder will be due within 60 days or set up payment plan. Failure to pay will be civil judgment.

$150.00 restititution to be paid to the Clerk of Court Office on behalf of Matthew Elling. Bond to be applied to restitution and any remainder to be paid within 60 days or set up payment plan. Failure to pay will be civil judgment.

Must provide DNA sample and pay the $200.00 DNA surcharge to be paid to Probation while on Probation. If not paid by end of Probation may be reduced to a civil judgment.  Defendant may request expungement of the DNA sample under Wis. Stat. 165.77(4) by petitioning the Wisconsin Department of Justice. Expungement of DNA is NOT a court process. 
For information see: http://www.doj.state.wi.us/dles/crime-labs/clb-forms.
No abusive contact with Matthew Elling.
Eligible for expungment upon successful completion of Probation.  Must petition court.
